I think the origin is in the phrase, &quot;Will the dogs eat the dog food?&quot; which was common VC-speak in the 90&#x27;s and 00&#x27;s, referencing dog food commercials that once ran on TV, and meaning something like &quot;this has been made to sound great in an internal powerpoint presentation, but will customers actually like it?&quot;<p>Attributed to a Microsoft exec in the 80s:
<a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.geekwire.com&#x2F;2025&#x2F;eat-your-own-dog-food-how-microsoft-popularized-one-of-the-yuckiest-terms-in-tech-history&#x2F;" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.geekwire.com&#x2F;2025&#x2F;eat-your-own-dog-food-how-micr...</a><p>In 2015, Marc Andreessen memorably said of Mixpanel&#x27;s success at product-led growth: &quot;The dogs are fucking jumping through the screen door to eat the dog food. And he hasn’t done any marketing yet.&quot;
<a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.newyorker.com&#x2F;magazine&#x2F;2015&#x2F;05&#x2F;18&#x2F;tomorrows-advance-man" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.newyorker.com&#x2F;magazine&#x2F;2015&#x2F;05&#x2F;18&#x2F;tomorrows-adva...</a><p>That then led to the idea of &quot;eating your own dog food&quot;, because if even you won&#x27;t eat it, what credibility do you have saying that the other dogs will?
